{{Good article}}
{{pp-move-indef}}
[[file:cerne-abbas-giant-2001-cropped.jpg|thumb|Cerne Abbas Giant chalk figure below the rectangular "Trendle" earthworks ]]
The '''Cerne Abbas Giant''' is a [[hill figure]] near the village of [[Cerne Abbas]] in [[Dorset]], [[England]]. Made by a turf-cut outline filled with chalk, it depicts a large, naked man, typically described as a [[giant (mythology)|giant]], wielding a club. The figure is listed as a [[scheduled monument]] in the United Kingdom and the site where he stands is owned by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]].

The figure has been the subject of much study and speculation, but its origin and age are unclear. It is often thought of as an ancient construction, though the earliest mention of it dates to the late 17th century. Early antiquarians associated it, on little evidence, with a [[Saxons|Saxon]] deity, while other scholars sought to identify it with a [[Celts|Celtic]] [[Britons (historical)|British]] figure or the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[Heracles|Hercules]], or some syncretization of the two. Archaeological evidence that parts of the drawing have been lost over time strengthen the Hercules identification. However the lack of earlier descriptions leads modern scholars to conclude that it may date from the 17th century, and perhaps originated as political satire.

Regardless of its age, the Cerne Abbas Giant has become an important part of local culture and folklore, which often associates it with [[fertility]]. It is one of England's best known hill figures and is a major visitor attraction in the region.

==Description==
[[file:cerne-abbas-giant-1891-ordnance-survey.jpg|thumb|Cerne Abbas Giant on 1891 [[Ordnance Survey]] map (1:10,560)<ref>"England - Dorset", Ordnance Survey map 1:10,560, Epoch 1 (1891)</ref>]]
The Cerne Abbas Giant is located just outside the small village of [[Cerne Abbas]] in [[Dorset]], about {{Convert|30|mi|abbr=on}} west of [[Bournemouth]] and {{Convert|16|mi|abbr=on}} north of [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]]. The figure depicts a huge naked man, about {{convert|55|m|abbr=on|disp=flip}} high and {{convert|51|m|abbr=on|disp=flip}} wide. It is carved into the white chalk rock <ref name="antiquity" /> on the steep west-facing side of a hill known as Giant Hill<ref name="heritage">"[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1003202 Hill figure called The Giant]", Scheduled Monument record number 1003202, The National Heritage List for England, at English Heritage, retrieved 14 October 2012.</ref> or Trendle Hill.<ref name="hiddenhistory2009">Haughton, Brian, ''Hidden History: Lost Civilizations, Secret Knowledge, and Ancient Mysteries'', publisher ReadHowYouWant.com, 2009, ISBN 1442952601, 9781442952607, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AWhGmlxrad0C&lpg=PA258&ots=qJNOr9ut1x&dq=cerne%20giant%20%22trendle%20hill%22%20%22giant%20hill%22&pg=PA258#v=onepage&q=giant%20hill%20trendle&f=false page 258]</ref><ref name="holloway">William Holloway, "The Giant of Trendle Hill", The minor minstrel: or, Poetical pieces, chiefly familiar and descriptive, Printed for W. Suttaby, 1808,     182 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UpkuAAAAYAAJ&dq=cerne%20giant&pg=PA140#v=onepage&q=cerne%20giant&f=false page 140]</ref> Atop the hill is another landmark, the Iron Age [[Earthworks (archaeology)|earthwork]] known as the "Trendle" or "Frying Pan".<ref name=hutchins>{{cite book |last=Hutchins |first=John |others=Robert Douch (Contributor) |title=The History and Antiquities of the County of Dorset |origdate= |origyear=1742 |origmonth= |url= |format= |accessdate= |edition= |series= |volume= |date= |year=1973 |month= |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers |location=Oxford |language= |isbn=0-87471-336-6 |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages= |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= }}</ref> The carving is formed by outlines cut into the turf about {{convert|0.6|m|abbr=on|disp=flip}} deep, and filled with crushed [[chalk]].<ref name="heritage" /> In his right hand the giant holds a knobbled [[Club (weapon)|club]] {{convert|120|ft|abbr=on}} in length,<ref>Hy. Colley March M.D. F.S.A., "The Giant and the Maypole of Cerne", ''Proceedings'', Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society, Vol.22, 1901, [http://archive.org/stream/proceedings22dorsuoft#page/108/mode/2up page 108]</ref> and adding {{convert|35|ft|abbr=on}} to the total height of the figure.<ref name="antiquity">Stuart Piggott, "The Hercules Myth<U+2014>beginnings and ends", ''Antiquity'' [http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/012/47/default.htm Vol.12 No.47], September 1938, Page 327</ref> A line across the waist is considered to be a belt.<ref>Timothy Darvill, "[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gzEclkBq0u0C&pg=PT208&lpg=PT208&dq=cerne+giant Cerne Giant, Dorset, England]", in ''Concise Oxford Dictionary of Archaeology'', publisher: Oxford University Press, 2009, ISBN 0199534047, 9780199534043, 544 pages.</ref> Writing in 1901 in the ''Proceedings'' of the Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society, Henry Colley March noted that: "The Cerne Giant presents five characteristics: (1) It is [[petrographic]] ... It is, therefore, a rock carving ... (2) It is colossal ... (3) It is nude. ... (4) It is [[ithyphallic]] ... (5) The Giant is clavigerous. It bears a weapon in its right hand."<ref>Hy. Colley March M.D. F.S.A., "The Giant and the Maypole of Cerne", ''Proceedings'', Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society, Vol.22, 1901, [http://archive.org/stream/proceedings22dorsuoft#page/106/mode/2up pages 107-108]</ref>

A 1996 study found that some features have changed over time, concluding that the figure originally held a cloak in its left arm and stood over a disembodied head.<ref name=Koch395>{{Cite book|last= Koch|first= John T.|coauthors= |title= Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia| publisher= ABC-CLIO|year= 2006|page= 395|isbn=1-85109-440-7}}</ref> The former presence of a cloak was corroborated in 2008 when a team of [[archaeology|archaeologists]] using special equipment determined that part of the carving had been allowed to be obliterated. The cloak may have been a depiction of an animal skin, giving credence to the theory that the giant was a depiction of a hunter, or alternatively, [[Hercules]] with the skin of the [[Nemean lion]] over his arm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weymouth.gov.uk/home.asp?sv=295 |title=Cerne Abbas Giant & Cerne Abbas, Dorset |accessdate=2010-10-03 |publisher=Weymouth & Portland Borough Council |date= }}{{dl|date=October 2012}}</ref> Additionally, reviewing historical depictions of the giant, it has been suggested that the Giant's current large erection is, in fact, the result of merging a circle representing his [[navel]] with a smaller penis during a re-cut.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Grinsell |first1= Leslie |year= 1980 |title= The Cerne Abbas Giant: 1764<U+2013>1980 | journal= Antiquity |volume= 54 |issue= 210 |pages= 29<U+2013>33 |publisher= |doi= |url= }}</ref> In 1993, the National Trust gave the Giant a "nose job" after years of erosion had worn it away.<ref>Chris Court, "Nose Job for Chalk Giant", Press Association, Sunday 11 April 1993, Home News</ref><ref>Raphael Samuel, ''Theatres of Memory: Past and Present in Contemporary Culture'', Publisher: Verso Books, 2012, ISBN 1844678695, 9781844678693, 508 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ptjYXlhmyP0C&lpg=PA172&dq=cerne%20giant&pg=PA172#v=onepage&q=cerne%20giant&f=false page 172]</ref>

The Giant has been described as "renowned for its manhood",<ref>Paul Edwards, "Campaigning Couples to Gather at Ancient Fertility Symbol", Press Association, Sunday 2 May 1993</ref> "markedly phallic",<ref name="antiquity" /> "sexually explicit"<ref>Temple Willcox, "Hard times for the Cerne Giant: 20th-century attitudes to an ancient monument" ([http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/062/Ant0620524.htm abstract]), ''Antiquity'', Vol.62 No.236, September 1988, page 524</ref> and "[[wiktionary:ithyphallic|ithyphallic]]".<ref>Hy. Colley March M.D. F.S.A., "The Giant and the Maypole of Cerne", ''Proceedings'', Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society, Vol.22, 1901, [http://archive.org/stream/proceedings22dorsuoft#page/108/mode/2up page 104]</ref> The Giant sports an erection, including its testicles, some {{Convert|36|ft|abbr=off}} long, and nearly the length of its head.<ref>Eugene Monick, ''Phallos: Sacred Image of the Masculine'', Volume 27 of Studies in Jungian psychology, publisher Inner City Books, 1987, ISBN 0919123260, 9780919123267, 141 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UKKP7wZDSPEC&lpg=PA36&dq=cerne%20giant&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q=cerne%20giant&f=false page 36]</ref> It has been called "Britain's most famous phallus".<ref name="Barnett2000" /> One commentator noted that postcards of the Giant were the only indecent photographs that could be sent through the English Post Office.<ref name="antiquity1976" />

The carving is most commonly known as the Cerne Abbas Giant.<ref name="books.google">John Sydenham, ''Baal Durotrigensis. A dissertation on the antient colossal figure at Cerne, Dorsetshire'', London, W. Pickering, 1842. "Section IV" ([http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Tv8GAAAAQAAJ&dq=%22Cerne%20Giant%22&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q=%22Cerne%20Giant%22&f=false page 43])</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/dorset/hi/people_and_places/nature/newsid_8571000/8571881.stm "Cerne Abbas Giant: Preserving an icon"], BBC News Dorset, Wednesday, 17 March 2010, retrieved 5 October 2012 </ref><ref>"[http://www.guardian.co.uk/travel/2010/jul/27/cerne-abbas-giant-dorset-fertility Pass notes no 2,820: The Cerne Abbas giant]", The Guardian, Tuesday 27 July 2010, retrieved 5 October 2012</ref><ref>"[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sponsored/travel/grand-adventure-holidays/8621225/Visit-the-Cerne-Abbas-Giant-in-Dorset.html Visit the Cerne Abbas Giant in Dorset]", 6 July 2011, retrieved 5 October 2012</ref> The [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] and others call it the "Cerne Giant",<ref>[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/cerne-giant/ "Cerne Giant"] at the National Trust, retrieved 5 October 2012</ref><ref name="books.google" /> while [[English Heritage]] and [[Dorset County Council]] call it simply "The Giant".<ref>"[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1003202 Hill figure called The Giant]" at English Heritage, retrieved 5 October 2012</ref><ref>"[http://www.dorsetforyou.com/389223 A background to Cerne Abbas]", Dorset County Council, retrieved 5 October 2012</ref> The carving has also been referred to as the "Old Man",<ref>"Notes of the Month", ''Antiquary, a magazine devoted to the study of the past'' (1905),Volume: 41, [http://archive.org/stream/antiquarymagazin41londuoft#page/364/mode/2up page 365]</ref> and more recently it has been referred to as the "Rude Man" of Cerne.<ref>Crispin Paine, ''Sacred Places'', National Trust Books, 2006, ISBN 1905400152, 9781905400157, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HpDFVMkCERYC&lpg=PA112&ots=-T6luEfWA1&dq=%22Rude%20Man%22%20cerne&pg=PA112#v=onepage&q=%22Rude%20Man%22%20cerne&f=false page 112]</ref><ref>Lionel Fanthorpe, Patricia Fanthorpe, ''The World's Most Mysterious Places'', Dundurn, 1999, ISBN 0888822065, 9780888822062, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hTRpldUOqfIC&lpg=PA171&ots=tYGEOz37wP&dq=%22Rude%20Man%22%20cerne&pg=PA171#v=onepage&q=%22Rude%20Man%22%20cerne&f=false page 171]</ref>

Although the best view of the Giant is from the air, most tourist guides recommend a ground view from the "Giant's View" [[Lay-by#Lay-bys|lay-by]] and car park off the A532.<ref>Patricia Beer, Fay Godwin, ''Wessex: a National Trust book'', published H. Hamilton, 1985, ISBN  0241115507, 9780241115503, 224 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=MY6SUIORDY2Y1AW5_ICgBg&id=k_l5AAAAIAAJ&dq=cerne+giant+%22+lay-by%22&q=%22lay-by%22#search_anchor page 132]</ref><ref>"[https://maps.google.co.uk/maps?hl=en Giant's View] Lay-By on the A532 in Cerne Abbas" on Google Maps, retrieved 1 November 2012</ref> This area was developed in 1979 in a joint project between  the Dorset County Planning Department, the [[National Trust]], Nature Conservancy Council (now called [[English Nature]]), the [[The Wildlife Trusts|Dorset Naturalists Trusts]], the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Department of the Environment]], and local land-owners. The information panel there was devised by the National Trust and [[Dorset County Council]].<ref>Tony Haskell, ''Caring for our Built Heritage: Conservation in practice: a review of conservation schemes carried out by County Councils and National Park Authorities in England and Wales in association with District Councils and other agencies'', Publisher Taylor & Francis, 1993, ISBN 0419175806, 9780419175803, 379 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4VqHd0kQL3YC&lpg=PA20&dq=cerne%20giant%20%22%20lay-by%22&pg=PA20#v=onepage&q=cerne%20giant%20%22%20lay-by%22&f=false page 20-21]</ref>

==History==
===Early accounts===
Like several other chalk figures carved into the English countryside, the Cerne Abbas Giant is often thought of as an ancient creation. However, as with many of the other figures, its history cannot be traced back further than the late 17th century, making an origin during the [[British Iron Age|Celtic]], [[Roman Britain|Roman]] or even [[Early Medieval]] periods difficult to demonstrate. Medieval sources do refer to the hill the giant is now on, calling it Trendle Hill - perhaps a reference to the nearby landmark known as the Trendle.<ref name="hiddenhistory2009" /><ref name=hutchins/> Joseph Bettey noted that none of the earlier sources for the area, including a detailed 1617 land survey, refer to the giant, suggesting that it may not have been there at the time.<ref name="bettey1981">J. H. Bettey, "The Cerne Abbas giant: the documentary evidence", ''Antiquity'', [http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/055/214/default.htm Vol.55, No.214], July 1981, pages 118.</ref> In contrast, the [[Uffington White Horse]] has been shown to be 3,000 years old, and there are references to it, across the ages.<ref>Martin Symington, ''Sacred Britain: A Guide to Places that Stir the Soul'', publisher: Bradt Travel Guides, 2012, ISBN 1841623636, 9781841623634, 240 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KTXOGXztZ-MC&lpg=PA53&dq=cerne%20giant%20uffington&pg=PA53#v=onepage&q=cerne%20giant%20uffington%20white%20horse&f=false page 53]</ref>

The earliest known written reference to the giant is a 4 November 1694 entry in the [[Churchwarden]]s' Accounts from St Mary's Church in Cerne Abbas, which reads "for repairing ye Giant, 3 shillings".<ref>Katherine Barker, "Brief Encounter: The Cerne Abbas Giantess Project, Summer 1997", ''Proceedings - Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society'', Volume 119, Page 179-183, citing Vale 1992, ''op.. cit'' [http://research.dorsetcountymuseum.org/c119.html][http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8tPaAAAAMAAJ&q=cerne+giant+1694&dq=cerne+giant+1694&source=bl&ots=QQpOmQ8xCR&sig=E_FDRi-j2bj_MHYJiB43oPpZPRg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GkVvUKjGKcXH0QXtrYC4Bg&ved=0CLYCEOgBMDA]</ref><ref>Vivian Vale, Patricia Vale, ''Book of Cerne Abbas: Abbey and After'', Halsgrove Press, 2000, ISBN 1841140694, 9781841140698</ref> In 1734, The [[Bishop of Bristol]] noted and inquired about the giant during a [[Canonical visitation|visitation]] to Cerne Abbas. The bishop's account, as well as subsequent observations such as those of [[William Stukeley]], were discussed at meetings of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]] in 1764.<ref name=Evans>D. Morgan Evans, "Eighteenth-Century Descriptions of the Cerne Abbas Giant", ''The Antiquaries Journal'', Volume 78, September 1998, [http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=7853264 page 463] (-471).</ref><ref name="stukeley1764">William Stukeley, ''Minute Book of the Society of Antiquaries'', Vol. IX, p.233. Thursday 15th March 1764. Reproduced in Hy. Colley March M.D. F.S.A., "The Giant and the Maypole of Cerne", ''Proceedings, Dorset Natural History and Archaeological Society, Vol.22, 1901', [http://archive.org/stream/proceedings22dorsuoft#page/116/mode/2up page 116].</ref> Additionally, in 1738 the antiquarian [[Francis Wise]] mentioned the giant in a letter.<ref>Francis Wise, ''A letter to Dr Mead concerning some antiquities in Berkshire'', printed for Thomas Wood, 1738, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cFAGAAAAQAAJ&lpg=PR92&ots=8_kFeqv9O4&dq=cerne%20giant&pg=PR90#v=onepage&q=cerne%20giant&f=false page 48]</ref>

Beginning in 1763 descriptions of the giant appeared in contemporary magazines. The earliest known survey was published in the ''Royal Magazine'' in September 1763. Derivative versions subsequently appeared in the October 1763 ''St James Chronicle'', the July 1764 ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'',<ref name="1874gentleman">''The Gentleman's Magazine'', Volume 34, July 1764, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6koDAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions%3AUOM39015018405376&lr&pg=PA336-IA1#v=onepage&q&f=false Page 336]</ref> and the 1764 edition of ''[[The Annual Register]]''.<ref name=Evans/><ref>''The Gentleman's magazine'', Volume 34 (August 1764). [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6koDAAAAMAAJ&dq=editions%3AUOM39015018405376&lr&pg=PA336#v=onepage&q=giant&f=false Page 335]
</ref><ref name=Haughton>{{cite book |title=Hidden History: Lost Civilizations, Secret Knowledge, and Ancient Mysteries |last=Haughton |first=Brian |year=2007 |publisher=New Page Books |location=Franklin Lakes, NJ |isbn=1-56414-897-1 |pages=136 }}</ref><ref name=Lewis>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Lewis |title=Celebrating May Day the Pagan Way |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/travel/2005/may/01/unitedkingdom.culturaltrips.observerescapesection1 |work= |publisher=''The Observer'' |date= 1 May 2005 |accessdate=20 June 2008}}</ref><ref>Robert Dodsley, ''The Annual Register'', 1764, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gJlGAAAAcAAJ&lpg=RA1-PA166&ots=_v2CDhSbEZ&dq=cerne%20giant&pg=RA1-PA166#v=onepage&q=giant&f=false page 166]</ref> The ''Gentleman's Magazine'' account in particular was prominent, and contained the oldest known drawing of the figure.<ref name=Evans/><ref name="1874gentleman" /> In 1774, the antiquarian [[John Hutchins (antiquary)|John Hutchins]] reviewed various previous accounts in his book ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Dorset''.<ref name=Evans/> In it, he wrote that the carving had only been done the previous century.<ref name=hutchins/>

The earliest known drawing of the Giant appears in the August 1764 issue of ''Gentleman's Magazine''.<ref name="1874gentleman" /> A map referred to as the "1768 Survey Map of Cerne Abbas by Benjamin Pryce" is held at the Dorset History Centre.<ref>"[http://www.cerneabbashistory.org/?page_id=107 Maps & Survey]",Cerne Abbas Historical Society, retrieved 13 October 2012 ([http://www.cerneabbashistory.org/pdfdocs/1798_SURVEY.pdf illustration])</ref> However, a record at the National Archives notes that "the cartouche refers to Lord Rivers by that title which he did not acquire until 1776. Numbers on the map appear to correspond with the survey of 1798"<ref>"Pitt-Rivers Estate Archive, Cerne Abbas map [https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=031-dpit&cid=4-1-4-2#4-1-4-2 D/PIT/P6?1768-1798]" at the National Archives, retrieved 13 October 2012 </ref>

