===Interpretation===
[[File:Cerne Abbas Giant (obliterated section restored).svg|thumb|Layout of the giant with the obliterated line (in yellow) reconstructed]]
There are three main ideas concerning the age of the Giant, and who he might represent:<ref>"[http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=MNA138903&resourceID=6 Cerne Abbas Giant, Hill-Figure]", National Trust Historic Buildings, Sites and Monuments Record (HBSMR) Number 110511, via the English Heritage Gateway, retrieved 30 October 2012</ref>
#The first argues that because there is no medieval documentary evidence, then the Giant was created in the 17th century, perhaps by [[Denzil Holles, 1st Baron Holles|Lord Holles]] who resided in Cerne Abbas, and perhaps as a parody of Oliver Cromwell.<ref>"[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/cerne-giant/ Cerne Giant]", National Trust website, retrieved 30 October 2012</ref>
#The second idea is that the Giant dates to the time of the Romans in Britain (i.e. [[Romano-British culture|Romano-British]]) because the Giant resembles the  Roman god [[Hercules]], who was based on the Greek god [[Heracles]].
#The third idea is that the Giant is of [[Celts|Celtic]] origin because it is stylistically similar to a Celtic god on a [[Frying pan|skillet]] handle found at [[Hod Hill]], Dorset, and dated to around  AD 10 to AD 51.

Various studies on the Cerne Abbas Giant have been undertaken since then. In 1896 the Somersetshire Archaeological and Natural History Society noted the consensus of members that the giant "is of very great antiquity".<ref>''Proceedings of the Somersetshire Arch<U+00E6>ological and Natural History Society'', 1896, [http://archive.org/stream/proceedingsvolu03socigoog#page/n30/mode/2up page 14]</ref> Modern scholarship largely rejects this, and argues for an origin shortly before the 18th century.<ref name=Koch396>{{Cite book|last= Koch|first= John T.|coauthors= |title= Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia| publisher= ABC-CLIO|year= 2006|page= 396|isbn=1-85109-440-7}}</ref> Modern histories of the Cerne Giant have been published by Bettey 1981, Legg 1990, and Darvill et al. 1999.<ref>"Cerne Abbas", [http://www.dorsetforyou.com/392997 The Dorset Historic Towns Project report on Cerne Abbas], "Part 3 and 4 Context and sources (pdf, 492kb)" 4.1 Previous research, page 21</ref>

Early antiquarians associated the figure with a [[Saxons|Saxon]] god whose name contained some variant of the element ''Hel-''.<ref name=Koch395396>{{Cite book|last= Koch|first= John T.|coauthors= |title= Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia| publisher= ABC-CLIO|year= 2006|pages= 395<U+2013>396|isbn=1-85109-440-7}}</ref> This god is attested in several medieval and early modern texts, and was associated with the Cerne Abbas Giant by an editor of a 1789 edition of [[William Camden]]'s ''Britannia'' and by [[William Stukeley]], who indicated that locals referred to the giant as "Helis".<ref name=Koch396/> A Saxon origin is unlikely, but Stukeley was also the first to hypothesize that the figure was [[Heracles|Hercules]], a suggestion that has found more support.<ref name=Koch396/><ref>''The modern antiquarian'', Julian Cope, Thorsons 1998</ref> Some 19th century sources describe the giant as having "between his legs, three rude letters, scarcely legible, and over them in modern figures, 748", (''rude'' meaning "roughly cut") and being the representation of Cenric, the son of [[Cuthred of Wessex|Cuthred]], King of Wessex.<ref>{{cite book |title=The London Encyclopaedia: Or, Universal Dictionary of Science, Art, Literature, and Practical Mechanics, Comprising a Popular View of the Present State of Knowledge. Illustrated by Numerous Engravings, a General Atlas, and Appropriate Diagrams |last=Curtis|first=Thomas (ed.)|year=1829|publisher=[[Thomas Tegg]]|location= |isbn=|pages=768|url=http://books.google.com/?id=7n9MAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA290&dq=%22trendle+hill%22#PPA291,M1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Beauties of England and Wales, Or, Delineations, Topographical, Historical, and Descriptive, of Each County |last=Britton|first=John, et al.|year=1803|publisher=Thomas Maiden, for Vernor and Hood|location= |isbn=|pages=|url=http://books.google.com/?id=cqQMAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA483&dq=%22trendle+hill%22#PPA483,M1}}</ref>

Proponents of a 17th-century origin suggest that the giant was carved during the [[English Civil War]] by servants of the [[Lord of the Manor]], [[Denzil Holles, 1st Baron Holles|Denzil Holles]], and was intended as a [[parody]] of [[Oliver Cromwell]].<ref name="sd">[http://www.sacred-destinations.com/england/cerne-abbas-giant.htm Cerne Abbas Giant at Sacred Destinations]</ref>Cromwell was sometimes mockingly referred to as "England's Hercules" by his enemies. The Hercules connection is strengthened by the 1996 discovery of the cloak, as Hercules was often depicted with a cloak made from the [[Nemean Lion]]'s skin.<ref name=Koch396/>

===Modern history===
In 1920, the giant and the {{convert|1|acre|m2|abbr=on}} site where he stands was donated to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] by its then land-owners, Alexander and George [[Pitt-Rivers]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Grinsell |first1= Leslie |year= 1980 |title= The Cerne Abbas Giant: 1764<U+2013>1980 | journal= Antiquity |volume= 54 |issue= 210 |page= 30 |publisher= |doi= |url= }}</ref> and it is now listed as a [[Scheduled Monument]].<ref>"[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1003202 Hill figure called The Giant]",List entry Number: 1003202, at english-heritage.org.uk, retrieved 20 October 2012</ref> During [[World War II]] the giant was camouflaged with brushwood by the Home Guard in order to prevent use as a landmark for enemy aircraft.<ref>Lucy Cockcroft, "Cerne Abbas giant in danger of disappearing", ''The Telegraph'', 19 June 2008, retrieved 6 October 2012</ref><ref>"[http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/2008/sep/16/heritage.ruralaffairs Volunteers restore historic giant of Cerne Abbas to his former glory]", ''The Guardian'', Tuesday 16 September 2008, retrieved 6 October 2012</ref>

According to the National Trust, the grass is trimmed regularly and the giant is fully re-chalked every 25 years.<ref>"[http://web.archive.org/web/20110629042803/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-chl/w-countryside_environment/w-archaeology/w-archaeology-places_to_visit/w-archaeology-cerne_abbas_giant.htm Cerne Abbas Giant]", National Trust, retrieved 29 June 2011 (via the Internet Archive WayBackMachine)</ref> Traditionally, the National Trust has relied on sheep from surrounding farms to [[Grazing|graze]] the site.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lucy |last=Cockcroft |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Cerne Abbas giant in danger of disappearing |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/main.jhtml?xml=/earth/2008/06/19/eagiant119.xml |work= |publisher=''The Daily Telegraph'' |date=19 June 2008 |accessdate=20 June 2008}}</ref> However, in 2008 a lack of sheep, coupled with a wet spring causing extra plant growth, forced a re-chalking of the giant,<ref>{{cite news |first= |last=BBC |authorlink=BBC |coauthors= |title= Sheep shortage hits Giant's look |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/7465329.stm |work= |publisher=''BBC'' |date=20 June 20 |accessdate=20 June 2008}}</ref> with 17 tonnes of new chalk being poured in and tamped down by hand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/2008/sep/16/heritage.ruralaffairs|title=Volunteers restore historic giant of Cerne Abbas to his former glory|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=16 September 2008|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian Newspapers|accessdate=17 September 2008}}</ref> In 2006, the National Trust carried out the first wildlife survey of the Cerne Abbas Giant, identifying wild flowers including the [[green-winged orchid]], [[clustered bellflower]] and [[autumn gentian]], which are uncommon in England.<ref>Richard Savill, "[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1522028/Giant-can-help-rare-wildlife-to-flourish.html Giant can help rare wildlife to flourish]", ''The Telegraph'', 23 June 2006, retrieved 7 October 2012</ref>

In 1921 Walter Long of [[Gillingham, Dorset]] objected to the giant's nudity and conducted a campaign to either convert it to a simple nude, or to cover its supposed obscenity with a leaf.<ref>Temple Willcox, "Hard times for the Cerne Giant: 20th-century attitudes to an ancient monument" ([http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/062/Ant0620524.htm abstract]), ''Antiquity'', Vol.62 No.236, September 1988, page 524</ref> Long's protest gained some traction, including the support of two bishops,<ref name="antiquity1976">"Editorial: regarding the Home Office file, Obscene Publications: the Cerne Abbas Giant ([http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/SearchUI/Details?uri=C4768357 PRO HO 45/18033])", ''Antiquity'', [http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/050/198/default.htm Vol.50 No.198], June 1976, pages 93-94</ref><ref name="Barnett2000">Antony Barnett, "[http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2000/mar/05/antonybarnett.theobserver Bishop tried to gird the giant's loins]", ''The Observer'', 5 March 2000</ref> and eventually reached the Home Office.<ref name="antiquity1976" /> The Home Office considered the protest to be in humour, though the chief constable responded to say the office could not act against a protected scheduled monument.<ref name="antiquity1976" />

===Archaeology===
[[File:Ercole - Museo archeol. di MI - foto GD'O - 26-6-2003.JPG|thumb|right|Roman god Hercules holding a club and the [[Nemean lion]]-skin fur]]
A 1617 land survey of Cerne Abbas makes no mention of the Giant, suggesting that it may not have been there at the time.<ref name="bettey1981" /> The first published survey appeared in the September 1763 issue of ''Royal Magazine'',  reprinted in the October 1763 issue of ''St James Chronicle'', and also in the August 1764 edition of ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'' together with the first drawing that included measurments.<ref name=Evans/>

Egyptologist and archaeology pioneer, Sir [[Flinders Petrie]],<ref>Brian Fagan, ''Archaeologists: Explorers of the Human Past'', Oxford University Press, 2003, ISBN 0195119460, 9780195119466, 192 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nAfJ1xBD664C&lpg=PA72&dq=Egyptologist%20archaeology%20pioneer%2C%20Flinders%20Petrie&pg=PA72#v=onepage&q=Egyptologist%20archaeology%20pioneer,%20Flinders%20Petrie&f=false page 72]</ref> surveyed the Giant probably during the First World War, and published his results in a [[Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland|Royal Anthropological Institute]] paper in 1926.<ref>Leslie Grinsel, "The Cern Abbas Giant 1764<U+2013>1980", ''Antiquity'', [http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/054/210/default.htm Vol.54 No.210], March 1980, page 29</ref><ref name="petrie1926">W. M. F. Petrie, ''[http://www.cantab.net/users/michael.behrend/repubs/petrie_hfe/pages/index.html The Hill Figures of England]'', "III. The Giant of Cerne", Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland, Occasional Paper No. 7, 1926</ref> Petrie says that he made 220 measurements, and records slight grooves across the neck, and from the shoulders down to the armpits. He also notes a row of pits suggesting the place of the spine. He concludes that the Giant is very different from that of the [[Long Man of Wilmington]], and that from having been repeatedly cleaned, minor grooves may have been added.<ref name="petrie1926" />

In 1764, [[William Stukeley]] was one of the first people to suggest that the Giant resembles [[Hercules]] (Heracles).<ref name="stukeley1764" /> In 1938,  British archaeologist [[Stuart Piggott]] agreed, and like Hercules, should also be carrying a lion-skin.<ref>Stuart Piggott, "The Hercules Myth<U+2014>beginnings and ends", ''Antiquity'' [http://antiquity.ac.uk/ant/012/47/default.htm Vol.12 No.47], September 1938, Pages 326<U+2013>327</ref><ref>Julia De Wolf Addison, ''Classic Myths in Art: An Account of Greek Myths as Illustrated by Great Artists'', Reprinted by Kessinger Publishing, 2003 ISBN 0766176703, 9780766176706, 360 pages, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LkCjlir-ITgC&lpg=PA188&dq=hercules%20club%20lion%20skin%20illustrated&pg=PA188#v=onepage&q=hercules%20club%20lion%20skin%20illustrated&f=false page 188]</ref> In 1979, a resistivity survey was carried out, and together with drill samples, confirmed the presence of the lion-skin.<ref>"Cerne Giant", 1979 Resistivity survey by A J Clark, A D H Bartlett and A E U David,English Heritage, [http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archsearch/record.jsf?titleId=1836072 National Monuments Record 1058724]</ref> Another resistivity survey in 1995 also found evidence of a cloak and changes to the length of the phallus, but did not find evidence (as rumoured) of a severed head, horns, or symbols between the feet.<ref>"Cerne Giant", 1995 Resistivity survey by A J Clark, A D H Bartlett and A E U David,English Heritage, [http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archsearch/record.jsf?titleId=1870505 1066313]</ref>

====Earthworks====
North-east of the head of the Giant is an escarpment called Trendle Hill, on which are some earthworks now called The Trendle or Frying Pan.<ref name="NTADStrendle">"[http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archsearch/record.jsf?titleId=1784533 The Trendle, Possible Roman Rectangular Earthwork Enclosure]", National Trust Archaeological Data Service</ref> It is a scheduled monument in its own right.<ref>"[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1002725 Earthworks on Giant Hill]", List entry Number: 1002725, The National Heritage List for England</ref> Antiquarian John Hutchins wrote in 1872 that "These remains are of very interesting character, and of considerable extent. They consist of circular and other earthworks, lines of defensive ramparts, an avenue, shallow excavations, and other indications of a British settlement.<ref>Hutchins (1742), quoted in Dr Wake Smart, "The Cerne Giant", ''Journal of the British Archaeological Association'', Volume: 28, 1872, [http://archive.org/stream/journalofbritish28brit#page/64/mode/2up page 65]</ref>

Unlike the Giant, the earthworks belong to Lord Digby, rather than the National Trust. Its purpose is unknown, though it is thought to be the site of maypole dancing.<ref name="NTADStrendle" /> It has been considered to be Roman,<ref name="NTADStrendle" /> or perhaps an Iron-Age burial mound containing the tomb of the person represented by the Giant.<ref>James Dyer, ''Southern England: an archaeological guide'', publisher Noyes Press, 1973, pp. 81-82</ref><ref>"[http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=199018 The Trendle]", National Monuments Record Number 199018, English Heritage at pastscape.org.uk, retrieved 25 October 2012</ref>

==Folklore==
Whatever its origin, the giant has become an important part of the culture and folklore of Dorset. Some folk stories indicate that the image is an outline of the corpse of a real giant.<ref name=Koch396/> One story says the giant came from [[Denmark]] leading an invasion of the coast, and was beheaded by the people of Cerne Abbas while he slept on the hillside.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Social Circulation of the Past: English Historical Culture 1500<U+2013>1730 |last=Woolf |first=Daniel R. |year=2003 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location= |isbn=0-19-925778-7 |pages=348, footnote 178 }}</ref>

Other folklore, first recorded in the [[Victorian era]], associates the figure with fertility.<ref name=Koch396/> In the past locals would erect a [[maypole]] on the earthwork, around which childless couples would [[fertility rite|dance to promote fertility]].<ref name=Lewis/> According to folk belief, a woman who sleeps on the figure will be blessed with fecundity, and infertility may be cured through sexual intercourse on top of the figure, especially the phallus.<ref name=Koch396/>

In 1808, Dorset poet William Holloway published his poem "The Giant of Trendle Hill",<ref name="holloway" /> in which the Giant is killed by the locals by piercing its heart.

==Media==
[[File:CerneAbbasHomer.jpg|thumb|right|Homer Simpson as promotion for ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''.]]
In modern times the giant has been used for several [[publicity stunt]]s and as an [[Advertising|advertisement]]. For example, Ann Bryn-Evans of the Pagan Federation recalls that the Giant has been used to promote "...condoms, jeans and bicycles."<ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/dorset/6901543.stm Wish for rain to wash away Homer]", BBC News, Monday, 16 July 2007</ref>

In 1998, pranksters Jeff Boardman and Ben Jones made a pair of jeans out of plastic mesh with a {{Convert|21|m|adj=on}} inside leg, and fitted them to the giant.<ref>"Giant's blue jeans stunt faces a pounds 5,000 demand", ''The Birmingham Post'', 15 May 1998</ref> to publicise American Jeans manufacturer Big Smith.<ref>Tina Rowe, "Giant cover-up is a stroke of pure jean-ius...;", ''Western Daily Press'', 15 May 1998, page 3</ref> In 2002, the BLAC advertising agency <ref>BLAC Agency for the Family Planning Association, [http://blacagency.com/?blac_work=family-planning-association campaign overview], retrieved 11 October 2012</ref> on behalf of "... the [[Family Planning Association]] (FPA) as part of its mission to promote condom-wearing [..] donned balaclavas and spent Sunday night rolling the enormous latex sheet down the Giant's member."<ref>"[http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/news/155079/DIARY-Arnold-covers-back-giant-condom-assault-UFO-spottersruse/?DCMP=ILC-SEARCH Diary: Arnold covers back in giant condom assault with UFO spotters ruse]", ''Campaign'', Friday, 9 August 2002</ref>

As a publicity stunt for the opening of ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]'' on the 16 July 2007, a giant [[Homer Simpson]] brandishing a [[doughnut]] was outlined in water-based [[Biodegradation|biodegradable]] paint to the left of the Cerne Abbas giant. This act angered local [[Neopaganism|neopagans]], who pledged to perform rain magic to wash the figure away.<ref name="Pagans have a cow over Homer">{{cite news|title=Pagans have a cow over Homer|publisher=The Sun Online |date=16 July 2007|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,2-2007320865,00.html}}</ref><ref name="Wish for rain to wash away Homer">{{cite news|title=Wish for rain to wash away Homer|publisher=BBC News|date=16 July 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/dorset/6901543.stm}}</ref>

In August 2007 a report in the ''[[Dorset Echo]]'' said that a man claiming to be the "Purple Phantom" had painted the Giant's penis purple. It was reported that the man was from [[Fathers 4 Justice]] but the group said that they did not know who it was.<ref>[http://www.thisisdorset.net/news/tidnews/display.var.1645001.0.giant_daubed_by_vigilante.php Giant daubed by 'vigilante']</ref>

The Cerne Abbas Giant has appeared in several films and TV programmes, including the title sequence of the 1986 British historical drama film [[Comrades (film)|Comrades]],<ref>"[http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0092772/locations Filming locations for Comrades]" at imdb.com, retrieved 12 October 2012</ref> a 1996 episode of the Erotic Tales series "The Insatiable Mrs Kirsch", directed by [[Ken Russell]] (featuring a replica of the Giant), in 1997, the series 5 finale "Sofa" of the comedy series [[Men Behaving Badly]], and the 2000 film, [[Maybe Baby (2000 film)|Maybe Baby]] directed by Ben Elton.<ref>"[http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E0qKZmROl7A&t=2m Maybe Baby]" end scene on YouTube.com, retrieved 12 October 2012</ref><ref>See the individuals productions, and "[http://south-central-media.co.uk/chrono_list/chrono_list.htm The South-Central Region On Screen]", retrieved 12 October 2012.</ref>

In 2012, pupils and  members of the local community recreated the Olympic torch on the Giant, to mark the passing of the official torch in the run-up to the 2012 London Olympics.<ref>Ruth Meech, "[http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/9732051.Youngsters_recreate_Olympic_torch_on_Cerne_Abbas__chalk_giant/ Youngsters recreate Olympic torch on Cerne Abbas' chalk giant]", ''Dorset Echo'',  Tuesday 29th May 2012, retrieved 27 October 2012</ref><ref>Emily Fairbairn, "Cerne Abbas Giant is biggest Olympic torchbearer", The Sun, 29th May 2012, retrieved 27 October 2012</ref>

===Representations===
In 1980, Devon artist Kenneth Evans-Loud, planned to produce a companion {{Convert|230|ft|adj=on}} female figure on the opposite hill, featuring [[Marilyn Monroe]] in her iconic pose from the film ''[[The Seven Year Itch]]'' where her dress is blown by a subway grating.<ref>Annabel Ferriman, "Objections to hill figure", ''The Times'', issue No. 60571, Monday, 10 March 1980, page 2.</ref><ref>
Rodney Castleden, ''The Cerne Giant'', Dorset Publishing Company, 1996, ISBN 0948699558, 9780948699559, [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=du2fAAAAMAAJ&q=%22kenneth+evans-loude%22&dq=%22kenneth+evans-loude%22&source=bl&ots=wJwUXS54hg&sig=m_fkcrMwkaQH14Fnp_pRJ3zwVDU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=hnt5ULaAGMvK0AWQooDIBw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA page 37]</ref>

In 1989, Turner Prize winning artist, [[Grayson Perry]] designed a set of motorbike leathers, inspired by the Cerne Abbas Giant.<ref>Naomi West, "[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3663237/The-world-of....html The world of...]", ''The Telegraph'', 17 February 2007, retrieved 11 October 2012</ref><ref>"Grayson Perry at the British Museum", ''The Vintage'', Thursday, December 15, 2011</ref><ref>"[http://liveweb.archive.org/http://londonersdiary.standard.co.uk/2011/03/saucy-tips-for-the-ladies-who-lunch.html Saucy tips for the ladies who lunch]", London Evening Standard, 10 March 2011, retrieved 11 October 2012</ref> In 1994, girls from [[Roedean School]] painted an {{convert|80|ft|adj=on}} replica of the Giant on their playing field, the day before sports day.<ref>Jack O'Sullivan, "[http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/so-you-still-want-to-send-the-kids-to-boarding-school-1081328.html So you still want to send the kids to boarding school?]", ''The Independent'', Thursday 18 March 1999, retrieved 12 October 2012</ref> In 1999, a plaque was discovered near the nose of the [[Marree Man]], a modern [[geoglyph]] discovered a year earlier, "claiming that a clue to its origins are to be found buried in a sealed container near the Cerne Giant".<ref>Molly Watson, "Mystery of the Aboriginal man leads to Dorset", ''The Evening Standard'' (London), 21 January 1999, page 18</ref><ref>Christopher Zinn, "English giants hold key to big Maree mystery", ''The Guardian'', Wednesday 20 January 1999</ref>

In 2003, pranksters created their own {{convert|75|ft|adj=on}} version of the Giant on a hill in [[English Bicknor]], but "wearing wellies, an ear of corn hanging from its mouth and a tankard of ale in its hand".<ref>"[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-23020884_ITM Pranksters Create A Naked Giant Imposter]",  ''Western Daily Press'', 15 April 2003, page 23</ref> In 2005, the makers of Lynx deodorant created a {{convert|100,000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} advert on a field near Gatwick, featuring a copy of the Giant wearing underpants, frolicking with two scantily-clad women.<ref>"Huge deodorant advert washed away", ''BBC News'', Tuesday, 26 July, 2005, retrieved 27 October 2012</ref> In 2006, artist Peter John Hardwick produced a painting "The Two Dancers with the Cerne Abbas Giant, with Apologies to Picasso" that is on display at Poole Hospital NHS Foundation Trust.<ref>Peter John Hardwick, "[http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/the-two-dancers-with-the-cerne-abbas-giant-with-apologies-59905 The Two Dancers with the Cerne Abbas Giant, with Apologies to Picasso]", BBC Your Paintings, retrieved 12 October 2012</ref> In 2009, the Giant was given a red nose, to publicize the BBC's Comic Relief charity event.<ref>"Cerne Abbas Giant given red nose", BBC News Dorsets, 12 February 2009, retrieved 12 October 2012</ref> In 2011, English animators, [[The Brothers McLeod]] produced a 15-second cartoon giving their take, on what the Giant does when no one is watching.<ref>The Brothers McLeod, "[http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/clips/p00krgw1/funny_in_15_seconds_funny_in_15_cerne_abbas/ Funny in 15: Cerne Abbas]", 29 September 2011, retrieved 12 October 2012</ref>

